===Etymology===
From {{der|en|xno|pollutiun}}, from {{der|en|frm|pollution}}, {{m|frm|pollucion}}, and their source, post-classical {{der|en|la|pollutio||defilement, desecration; nocturnal emission}} (4th century), from the participial stem of Latin {{m|la|polluere||to soil, defile, contaminate}}, from {{m|la|por-||before}} + {{m|la|-luere||to smear}}, related to {{m|la|lutum||mud}} and {{m|la|lues||filth}}. Compare Greek {{m|grc|||filth, dirt, disgrace}} and {{m|grc|||rubbish, refuse}}, Old Irish {{m|sga|loth||mud, dirt}}, Lithuanian {{m|lt|lutynas||pool, puddle}}.
